outcomes.title: Continuity Specific
outcomes.description: I can show that a function is continuous over a given interval.
outcomes.template:
Show that Q(t) = {{Qt}} is continuous for any c such that {{a}} < c < {{b}}.

Notice that Q(c) = {{Qc}}. Thus we have: |Q(t)-Q(c)| = |\left({{Qt}}\right) - \left({{Qc}}\right)| = | {{simp1}} - {{simp2}} | = {{k}}\cdot |{{factor}}| \cdot |t-c| \leq {{k}} \cdot \left( {{absfactor}} \right)\cdot |t-c| < {{k}} \cdot {{n}} \cdot {{maxab}}^{ {{nm1}} }\cdot |t-c| = {{M}}\cdot |t-c| So by letting M={{M}} we have shown that Q(t) = {{Qt}} is continuous for any c where {{a}} < c < {{b}}

Notice that Q(c) = {{Qc}}. outcomes.description: I can show that a function is continuous over a general interval.
outcomes.template:
Show that Q(t) = {{Qt}} is continuous for any c such that {{lb}} < c < {{ub}}.

Notice that Q(c) = {{Qc}}. Thus we have: |Q(t)-Q(c)| = |\left({{Qt}}\right) - \left({{Qc}}\right)| = | {{simp1}} - {{simp2}} | = {{k}}\cdot |{{factor}}| \cdot |t-c| \leq {{k}} \cdot \left( {{absfactor}} \right)\cdot |t-c| < {{k}} \cdot {{n}} \cdot \max(|{{lb}}|, |{{ub}}| )^{ {{nm1}} }\cdot |t-c| So by letting M={{k}} \cdot {{n}} \cdot \max(|{{lb}}|, |{{ub}}| )^{ {{nm1}} } we have shown that Q(t) = {{Qt}} is continuous for any c where {{lb}} < c < {{ub}}

Show that Q(t) = {{Qt}} is continuous for any c such that {{lb}} < c < {{ub}}.

Notice that Q(c) = {{Qc}}. Thus we have: |Q(t)-Q(c)| = |\left({{Qt}}\right) - \left({{Qc}}\right)| = \left| \frac{ ( {{Qt}})^2 - ( {{Qc}})^2 }{ {{denom}} } \right| = \left| \frac{ ({{k}}t - {{l}}) - ({{k}}c - {{l}}) }{ {{denom}} } \right| = \left| \frac{ {{k}}t - {{k}}c }{ {{denom}} } \right| = \left| \frac{ {{k}} }{ {{denom}} } \right| \cdot |t-c| < \left| \frac{ {{k}} }{ \sqrt{ {{k}}\cdot \min(|{{lb}}|, |{{ub}}|) - {{l}} } + \sqrt{ {{k}} \cdot \min(|{{lb}}|, |{{ub}}|) - {{l}} } } \right| \cdot |t-c| = \left| \frac{ {{k}} }{ 2\sqrt{ {{k}}\cdot \min(|{{lb}}|, |{{ub}}|) - {{l}} } } \right| \cdot |t-c| So by letting M=\left| \frac{ {{k}} }{ 2\sqrt{ {{k}}\cdot \min(|{{lb}}|, |{{ub}}|) - {{l}} } } \right| we have shown that Q(t) = {{Qt}} is continuous for any c where {{lb}} < c < {{ub}}

Notice that Q(c) = {{Qc}}. Notice that Q(c) = {{Qc}}. Thus we have: \frac{ \left({{Qt}}\right) - \left({{Qt}}\right) }{t-c} = \frac{ {{simp1}} - {{simp2}} }{ t-c } = {{k}}\cdot \left( {{factor}} \right). Using the bounds for c, t we have {{k}}\cdot \left({{n}}\cdot {{a}}^{ {{nm1}} } \right) < {{k}}\cdot \left({{factor}}\right) < {{k}}\cdot \left({{n}}\cdot {{b}}^{ {{nm1}} } \right), {{k}}\cdot \left({{LB}}\right) < {{k}}\cdot \left({{factor}}\right) < {{k}}\cdot \left({{UB}}\right), {{LBk}} < {{k}}\cdot \left( {{factor}} \right) < {{UBk}}

So the lower bound for \displaystyle \frac{Q(t)-Q(c)}{t-c} is {{LBk}} and the upper bound is {{UBk}}.

Find best lower and upper bounds for \displaystyle \frac{Q(t)-Q(c)}{t-c} where Q(t) = {{Qt}} and {{a}} < t, c < {{b}}.

Notice that Q(c) = {{Qc}}. Thus we have: \frac{Q(t)-Q(c)}{t-c} = \frac{ {{Qt}} -{{Qc}} }{t-c} = \frac{ ( {{Qt}})^2 - ( {{Qc}})^2 }{ {{denom}} } \cdot \frac{1}{t-c} = \frac{ ({{k}}t - {{l}}) - ({{k}}c - {{l}}) }{ {{denom}} } \cdot \frac{1}{t-c} = \frac{ {{k}}t - {{k}}c }{ {{denom}} } \cdot \frac{1}{t-c} = \frac{ {{k}} }{ {{denom}} } Using the bounds for c, t we have \frac{ {{k}} }{ 2\sqrt{ {{k}}\cdot {{a}} - {{l}} } } < \frac{ {{k}} }{ {{denom}} } < \frac{ {{k}} }{ 2\sqrt{ {{k}}\cdot {{b}} - {{l}} } }, {{k}}\cdot {{LB}} < \frac{ {{k}} }{ {{denom}} } < {{k}}\cdot {{UB}}, {{LBk}} < \frac{ {{k}} }{ {{denom}} } < {{UBk}},

So the lower bound for \displaystyle \frac{Q(t)-Q(c)}{t-c} is {{LBk}} and the upper bound is {{UBk}}.

Find best lower and upper bounds for \displaystyle \frac{Q(t)-Q(c)}{t-c} where Q(t) = {{Qt}} and {{a}} < t, c < {{b}}.
